uofang Li reveals illustrates the challenges of teaching and learning in an increasingly complex educational landscape in which literacy, culture, race, and social class intertwine. Advocating for a greater cultural understanding of minority beliefs in literacy education and a more critical examination of mainstream instructional practices, Li offers a new theoretical framework and critical recommendations for teachers, schools, and parents.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAsian AmericansxEducation. 0aAsiansxEducationzCanada. 0aChildren of immigrantsxEducationzCanada. 0aChildren of immigrantsxEducationzUnited States. 0aLiteracyxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aLiteracyxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aParent-teacher relationshipszCanada. 0aParent-teacher relationshipszUnited States. 4aEducation : Education. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Minority Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791482544423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791482544/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles